## Change 6 — Mobile layout fixes

This is the most important change. The current layout breaks on mobile because the
two-column sidebar + main approach requires explicit responsive handling.

### 6a — Root layout responsive CSS

In `app/globals.css`, ensure the layout wrapper switches to a single column on mobile.
Find wherever the two-column layout is defined (likely a flex or grid on the outer wrapper
in `app/layout.tsx`) and add/update:

```css
/* Desktop: sidebar left, content right */
.layout {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: row;
  min-height: 100vh;
  max-width: 1100px;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: 0 2rem;
}

/* Mobile: stack vertically */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .layout {
    flex-direction: column;
    padding: 0 1.25rem;
  }
}
```

### 6b — Sidebar mobile styles

In `components/Sidebar.tsx`, apply these responsive styles so the sidebar
stacks cleanly above the content on mobile:

```css
/* Sidebar container */
.sidebar {
  width: 200px;           /* desktop */
  padding-top: 5rem;
  flex-shrink: 0;
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .sidebar {
    width: 100%;
    padding-top: 2rem;
    padding-bottom: 1.5rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0;
  }
}
```

On mobile the sidebar nav links should:
- Display as a horizontal flex row for the primary nav (Home, Building, Blog, Archive)
- Wrap if needed
- Gap of 1.25rem between items
- Secondary links (Twitter, LinkedIn, GitHub, Email) stay vertical below, smaller font

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
